04178nam a22005655i 9780822382461DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t19971997ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223824617 a10.1515/97808223824612doi  a(DE-B1597)552965  a(OCoLC)1226678512  a(OCoLC)1125499652  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aP106b.L334 1997 7aLAN0000002bisacsh1 aLee, Benjamin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTalking Heads :bLanguage, Metalanguage, and the Semiotics of Subjectivity /cBenjamin Lee. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1997] 4cÂ©1997  a1 online resource (387 p.) :b3 figures, 5 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1 The Foundations of Performativity: Austin and Frege -- tChapter 2 Deconstructing Performativity -- tChapter 3 Reconstructing Performativity -- tChapter 4 Peirce's Semiotic -- tChapter 5 Linguistics and Semiotics -- tChapter 6 The Semiotic Mediation of Language and Thought -- tChapter 7 Metalinguistics and Philosophy -- tChapter 8 The Metalinguistics of Narration -- tChapter 9 The Performativity of Foundations -- tReference List -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Talking Heads, Benjamin Lee situates himself at the convergence of multiple disciplines: philosophy, linguistics, anthropology, and literary theory. He offers a nuanced exploration of the central questions shared by these disciplines during the modern era-questions regarding the relations between language, subjectivity, community, and the external world. Scholars in each discipline approach these questions from significantly different angles; in seeking to identify and define the intersection of these angles, Lee argues for the development of a new sense of subjectivity, a construct that has repercussions of immense importance beyond the humanities and into the area of politics.Talking Heads synthesizes the views and works of a breathtaking range of the most influential modern theorists of the humanities and social sciences, including Austin, Searle, Derrida, Jakobson, Bakhtin, Wittgenstein, Peirce, Frege, Kripke, Donnellan, Putnam, Saussure, and Whorf. After illuminating these many strands of thought, Lee moves beyond disciplinary biases and re-embeds within the context of the public sphere the questions of subjectivity and language raised by these theorists. In his examination of how subjectivity relates not just to grammatical patterns but also to the specific social institutions in which these patterns develop and are sustained, Lee discusses such topics as the concept of public opinion and the emergence of Western nation-states.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aLanguage and languagesxPhilosophy. 0aMetalanguage. 0aPerformative (Philosophy). 0aSemiotics. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999z978311071360240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822382461zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822382461423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822382461.jpg  a978-3-11-071360-2  DUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999c1964d1999  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles